The Life Esidimeni alternative dispute resolution process between the state and families of the victims is expected to start on Monday in Parktown. The hearing is expected to last for at least 15 days with the government and affected family members expected to testify. At least 110 psychiatric patients died between March and December last year after they were transferred from Life Esidimeni facilities to various NGOs. The process will be led by retired Deputy Chief Justice Dikgang Moseneke. During his briefing in September, Moseneke confirmed that at least 60 families have come forward, out of a potential 110 to claim from the government. So far, more than 57 patients have been relocated since the implementation of the Mental Health transfer project. With 28 psychiatric patients transferred to Selby Park Hospital in Johannesburg.